postcontent:
For sale is a Geco 26.5mm all steel flare pistol. The Geco is made in Germany and was imported into the US in fairly limited quantities in the early 2000's. Sportsman's Guide and several other retailers sold them inexpensively then. However today they are nearly impossible to find. In my opinion the Geco is the highest quality, strongest and most interesting of all of these type pistols brought to US during the last 20 years. Many feel that the HK is a better pistol however I've owned both and unlike the Geco - the only steel part on the HK is the barrel as the entire frame is plastic.

This Geco is in original UNFIRED condition. Also included in this package is:

26.5 mm to .410/.45 Long Colt adapter that allows 2.5" & 3" .410 shotgun ammo or .45LC ammo to be safely fired.

26.5mm to 12 gauge adapter that allows the less expensive 12 gauge flares to be fired. This adapter cannot be used with regular 12 gauge shotgun shells and must never be attempted as the results would be catastrophic.

Original German flap holster that is weather resistant and has room to store the pistol, cleaning brush, 26.5mm ammo, .410 or.45 ammo & one or both adapters. Holster also has a shoulder carry strap attached.

26.5mm cleaning brush and nylon lanyard strap for pistol

(3) 5 round boxes 2.5" .410 rifled slug ammo. (1) 25 round box of 3" - 00 buck with 5 pellets per shell, & (1) 25 round box 3" #7.5 shot (devastating close range defense load).

(2) 26.5mm white parachute illumination shells, (2) 26.5 mm Red Rain shells & (2) 26.5mm orange smoke shells.

(1) sealed 4 round package of Orion 12 gauge super red flares - expire July 2016

The last Geco I saw on Gunbroker was before Christmas and it sold for over $200 without accessories similar to what the HK's do when they come up for sale. So if you investigate and price everything included in this set - you'll see that my asking price is a bargain.

Price: $350 obo. Also this is a pickup item as shipping live flare shells is a hassle and it's costly. Also because this flare pistol becomes a real firearm if the .410 adapter is inserted you must be at least 21 to purchase.

title: For Sale:  1941 Nazi Browning Hi-Power 9mm P-35 German Occupation Army WWII Upgraded slide Belgium!
postcontent:
This is currently listed on Gun Broker and it is currently at $660 and it ends at 7pm tonight (In 9 hours).  40 photos available. Cut and paste this item number to view it:  333150282

Of course local pick-up and payment is available if you are the winner!

DESCRIPTION: This is truly one of a kind and the best of both worlds! (1)You have a very beautiful old Belgium made Browning produced during Nazi control. It is a German Occupational Army pistol with matching serial numbers on the frame and barrel. Both also have the Nazi Eagle over Swastika proof marks and designation of AaW140. (2)This also has been upgraded to a newer slide with the more reliable external extractor as well as an adjustable rear sight. (The original slide is no longer available). It truly is the best of both worlds. A great piece of history with matching serial numbers and the shootability and reliability of a newer slide! What a conversation piece!

BROWNING HISTORIAN: After contacting Glen, the Browning historian it was determined this exact pistol was produced for the German Occupational Army between 1940-1944. By the serial number the best info we can determine this was made approximately in 1941. With limited records, it is difficult to determine the exact date. If this pistol could talk I bet it would have some great stories to tell!

PROOF MARKINGS: The frame is marked with the German Eagle over swastika, the WaA140 acceptance mark, the front left side of the trigger guard is marked “MP” and the right side has the serial number “133019”. The barrel is marked with an “Eagle” and “133019”. The bottom of the frame next to the magazine well is marked “L”, “8”, “r”, and what appears to be a triangle. These are difficult to see, however if they are important, please request more details and we can try to view it with a jewelers loops.

SERIAL AND DATING: Belgium Browning manufactured approximately in 1941, a very low serial number with no prefix or suffix. The “133019” serial number is the lowest serial number I have viewed on Gunbroker or anywhere else!

SIGHTS: Improved newer slide with external extractor and adjustable rear sight. Blade front sight.

GRIPS: Original walnut grips in good condition. No cracks. Checkering still present and in good condition.

FINISH: It appears to have the original 70+ year old finish. Some holster wear. Back strap and underneath show more wear.

BARREL: Approximately 4 3/4" barrel with good bore and rifling.

ACTION: Very smooth and crisp action. This was not test fired, however we did fire it with a snap cap and the trigger feels good and sounds like the hammer hit the snap cap appropriately.

MAGAZINE: Not certain if this is the original magazine.

HISTORY: FN commissioned John Browning to design a new military sidearm conforming to this specification. Browning had previously sold the rights to his successful M1911 U.S. Army automatic pistol to Colt's Patent Firearms, and was therefore forced to design an entirely new pistol while working around the M1911 patents. Browning built two different prototypes for the project in Utah and filed the patent for this pistol in the United States on June 28, 1923 and granted on February 22, 1927.[5][6] One was a simple blowback design, while the other was operated with a locked-breech recoil system. Both prototypes utilized the new staggered magazine design (by designer Dieudonné Saive) to increase capacity without unduly increasing the pistol's grip size or magazine length. By 1931, the Hi-Power design incorporated a shortened 13-round magazine, a curved rear grip strap, and a barrel bushing that was integral to the slide assembly. By 1934, the Hi-Power design was complete and ready to be produced. It was first adopted by Belgium for military service in 1935 as the Browning P-35. Ultimately, France decided not to adopt the pistol, instead selecting the conceptually similar but lower-capacity Modèle 1935 pistol. Though many governments, the world wide and for decades have used this fantastic arm as a primary sidearm. (source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Browning_Hi-Power)


This is the best information we have on this unique piece. We encourage you to do your own research or ask any questions you have. We will do our best to answer with the information we were given. Please view photos carefully as this is in good condition for being approximately 72 years old!

A decent example of the “Made in Belgium”, FN Browning Auto-5, A5, standard (not Sweet 16), 16 ga semi-auto shotgun. Original Poly Choke (Hartford, Conn), and round knob stock & buttplate. Belgian (FN) made in 1954. All numbers I saw match, and barrel top reads: “Browning Arms Company, St. Louis, Mo.” In condition as you see it, not a show piece, but also not a bad looking gun. I disassembled, cleaned, oiled, and replaced the recoil and action springs (no problems were apparent but since the springs were probably original, and nearly 60 years old, it seemed like a good idea). Bore is bright and shiney, and I measure it at 27 1/2” from end of poly choke to where barrel meets receiver. Back stock is solid, front looks good as well with a small split that looks like it was repaired some time ago. This came to me as part of a multi-gun deal, since then I have had spinal fusion surgery and my docs have advised against any further shooting of higher recoil guns. I have not fired this, but see nothing that tells me it won’t shoot well and reliably, but it was made in 1954, so you should not expect NIB. Pictures tell the story.
